e19605bb-aab1-9a55-ba15-e15b3eaf65d3"}, "input": {"input": ["# Children's Adaptive Behavior and Mental Health Community\n\nThis community is centered around tools and conditions related to children's adaptive behavior and mental health, including the Children's Adaptive Behavior Rating Scale, Mental Retardation, and the Wechsler Intelligence Test. The entities are interconnected through their roles in diagnosing and assessing mental health conditions, particularly in children. The community also includes related conditions like Dementia and Korsakoff Syndrome, which are linked through their cognitive and neurological impacts.\n\n## Children's Adaptive Behavior Rating Scale as a key diagnostic tool\n\nThe Children's Adaptive Behavior Rating Scale is a central entity in this community, developed in 1990 in Changsha, China. It is used to assess the adaptive behavior development level of children aged 3 to 12, aiding in the diagnosis of mental retardation and the formulation of special training plans for intellectually disabled children. Its development in Changsha highlights its regional significance and its role in addressing mental health needs in children. [Data: Entities (1073, 1072); Relationships (1221, 1222)]\n\n## Mental Retardation as a core condition\n\nMental Retardation, also known as intellectual disability, is a key condition in this community. It is characterized by impaired cognitive and social functioning, typically diagnosed in individuals under 18 with an IQ below 70. The condition is classified into four levels—mild, moderate, severe, and profound—based on IQ and impairment extent. It impacts learning, communication, and daily living skills, requiring tailored support and interventions. [Data: Entities (1074)]\n\n## Wechsler Intelligence Test's role in diagnosing Mental Retardation\n\nThe Wechsler Intelligence Test is a critical tool used to diagnose Mental Retardation by assessing IQ. An IQ below 70 is one of the diagnostic criteria for the condition. This test plays a significant role in identifying individuals who may require specialized support and interventions. [Data: Entities (1076); Relationships (1224)]\n\n## Children's Social Ability Rating Scale for assessing social skills\n\nThe Children's Social Ability Rating Scale is used to assess social life abilities in children aged 6 months to 15 years. It is particularly relevant for children with Mental Retardation, as it helps evaluate their social adaptive abilities. This scale is an important tool in understanding and supporting the social development of children with intellectual disabilities. [Data: Entities (1075); Relationships (1225)]\n\n## Dementia and Korsakoff Syndrome as related conditions\n\nDementia and Korsakoff Syndrome are included in this community due to their cognitive and neurological impacts. Korsakoff Syndrome, a specific type of dementia caused by thiamine deficiency, is linked to Dementia through its severe cognitive decline. These conditions highlight the broader context of cognitive impairments within the community. [Data: Entities (1632, 1633); Relationships (1776)]\n\n## Historical significance of Kopcako B in identifying Korsakoff Syndrome\n\nKopcako B is noted for proposing the amnestic syndrome in 1887, which was later named Korsakoff Syndrome. This historical contribution underscores the long-standing recognition of cognitive impairments and their classification within the medical community. [Data: Entities (1712); Relationships (1841)]", "# DSM, ICD, and APA: Mental Health Classification Community\n\nThis community centers around the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM), the International Classification of Diseases (ICD), and the American Psychiatric Association (APA). The DSM, published by the APA, serves as a critical resource for standardizing mental health diagnoses in the United States, while the ICD acts as a global counterpart. The relationships between these entities highlight their roles in evolving mental health classification systems, with the DSM notably removing the classification of neurasthenia starting from its third edition.\n\n## DSM as a central resource for mental health diagnosis\n\nThe Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM) is a pivotal publication by the American Psychiatric Association (APA) that standardizes the classification and diagnosis of mental disorders in the United States. It provides a common language and criteria for mental health professionals, ensuring consistency in diagnosis and treatment. The DSM has undergone several revisions, reflecting evolving understandings in psychiatry, such as the removal of neurasthenia starting from its third edition. This evolution underscores the DSM's role in adapting to new research and clinical insights, maintaining its relevance in the field of mental health [Data: Entities (249), Relationships (311)].\n\n## APA's role in publishing and updating the DSM\n\nThe American Psychiatric Association (APA) is responsible for publishing and updating the DSM, which standardizes mental health diagnoses. The APA's involvement ensures that the DSM remains a critical resource for mental health professionals, incorporating the latest research and clinical insights. This relationship highlights the APA's influence in shaping mental health classification systems and its commitment to maintaining the DSM's accuracy and relevance [Data: Entities (427), Relationships (514)].\n\n## ICD as a global counterpart to the DSM\n\nThe International Classification of Diseases (ICD) serves as a global standard for classifying diseases, including mental disorders. While the DSM is specific to the United States, the ICD provides a broader, international framework for disease classification. The relationship between the ICD and DSM underscores the complementary roles these systems play in standardizing mental health diagnoses, with the DSM acting as the U.S. counterpart to the global ICD [Data: Entities (428), Relationships (515)].\n\n## Evolution of the DSM through multiple editions\n\nThe DSM has evolved through multiple editions, reflecting changes in the understanding and classification of mental disorders. For instance, the removal of neurasthenia starting from the third edition illustrates the DSM's adaptability to new research and clinical insights. This evolution ensures that the DSM remains a relevant and accurate resource for mental health professionals, continuously incorporating the latest advancements in the field [Data: Entities (249), Relationships (311)].\n\n## Significance of neurasthenia's removal from the DSM\n\nThe removal of neurasthenia from the DSM starting from its third edition marks a significant change in the classification of mental disorders. This decision reflects evolving understandings and diagnostic criteria within psychiatry, highlighting the DSM's role in adapting to new research and clinical insights. The removal of neurasthenia underscores the DSM's commitment to maintaining accurate and relevant diagnostic criteria, ensuring its utility for mental health professionals [Data: Entities (249), Relationships (311)].", "# Neurasthenia and Its Historical and Cultural Context\n\nThis community centers around the concept of neurasthenia, a condition historically characterized by chronic mental and physical fatigue. Key entities include Beard GM, who proposed the concept in 1869, and Mitchell SW, who developed a treatment plan. The condition's prevalence and recognition vary significantly across regions, with continued use in Eastern and developing countries but abandonment in Europe. The International Classification of Diseases, 10th Edition, retains the term but limits its use. The community also includes related conditions such as somatoform disorder and brain organic diseases, which must be ruled out before diagnosing neurasthenia.\n\n## Beard GM's foundational role in neurasthenia\n\nBeard GM is a pivotal figure in this community, having proposed the concept of neurasthenia in 1869. His work laid the groundwork for understanding the condition as a result of nerve force depletion and exhaustion, particularly in the context of industrialization. This historical perspective is crucial for understanding the evolution of medical thought regarding fatigue-related conditions. [Data: Entities (250), Relationships (312)]\n\n## Mitchell SW's treatment plan for neurasthenia\n\nMitchell SW contributed significantly to the community by proposing a detailed and attractive treatment plan for neurasthenia. His approach, which includes rest, nutrition, and massage, highlights the holistic methods historically used to address the condition. This treatment plan remains relevant in discussions about managing chronic fatigue and stress. [Data: Entities (251), Relationships (313)]\n\n## Regional variations in neurasthenia's recognition\n\nThe recognition and use of the term neurasthenia vary significantly across different regions. While the concept has been largely abandoned in Europe, it continues to be widely used and studied in Eastern and developing countries. This regional disparity reflects differing cultural perceptions and medical practices regarding fatigue-related conditions. [Data: Entities (257, 258, 259), Relationships (320, 321, 322)]\n\n## Neurasthenia in the International Classification of Diseases\n\nThe International Classification of Diseases, 10th Edition, retains the term neurasthenia but limits its use. This inclusion indicates the condition's historical significance and its continued relevance in certain medical contexts. The classification's stance on neurasthenia influences diagnostic practices and treatment approaches globally. [Data: Entities (254), Relationships (316)]\n\n## Yang Desen's explanation of neurasthenia's mechanism\n\nYang Desen is mentioned in the context of explaining the mechanism of neurasthenia using the concept of energy consumption. His work contributes to the understanding of the condition's physiological underpinnings, emphasizing the interplay between energy depletion and chronic fatigue. This perspective is valuable for developing targeted treatment strategies. [Data: Entities (279), Relationships (342)]\n\n## Neurasthenia's relationship with somatoform disorder\n\nNeurasthenia and somatoform disorder both involve physical symptoms, but somatoform disorder lacks a clear medical explanation. This distinction is important for accurate diagnosis and treatment, as it highlights the need to differentiate between conditions with similar presentations but different underlying causes. [Data: Entities (281), Relationships (346)]\n\n## Exclusion of brain organic diseases in neurasthenia diagnosis\n\nBrain organic diseases must be ruled out before diagnosing neurasthenia, as they can mimic its symptoms. This diagnostic criterion underscores the importance of thorough medical evaluation to ensure accurate identification and treatment of fatigue-related conditions. [Data: Entities (282), Relationships (350)]", "# ICD-10 Mental Disorders and Global Prevalence\n\nThe community centers around ICD-10 Mental Disorders, with a focus on their prevalence rates across various global regions. Key entities include Lecrubier and multiple regions such as Turkey Angora, Greece Athens, and India Bangalore, all of which are linked to the discussion of mental disorder prevalence. The relationships highlight the global scope of the issue, with each region reporting prevalence rates of ICD-10 mental disorders.\n\n## ICD-10 Mental Disorders as the central focus\n\nICD-10 Mental Disorders are the central entity in this community, with discussions revolving around their prevalence rates. This classification system is crucial for understanding mental health trends globally. The high degree of connections to various regions underscores its importance in public health research and policy-making. [Data: Entities (278), Relationships (323, 325, 327, 328, 329,